meta:
  origin:
    producer: Troeger et al.
    title: Rotavirus vaccination and the global burden of rotavirus diarrhea among children younger than 5 years
    description: |-
      This dataset presents findings from a study on the global burden of rotavirus diarrhea in children under five years old, drawing on statistics from the Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation (IHME) Global Burden of Disease study.

      The data includes estimated numbers of child deaths, child mortality rates, and numbers of cases attributable to rotavirus. It also provides estimates of deaths averted by the rotavirus vaccine and the number of potentially avertable deaths if full rotavirus vaccine coverage were achieved.

      Rotavirus is a diarrheal disease responsible for an estimated 29% of diarrheal disease deaths in children under five. Estimates of potentially avertable deaths account for regional variation in vaccine efficacy: while efficacy exceeds 90% in high-income countries, it is closer to 50% in lower-income settings such as Sub-Saharan Africa.
    citation_full: Troeger, C., Khalil, I. A., Rao, P. C., Cao, S., Blacker, B. F., Ahmed, T., ... and Kang, G. (2018). Rotavirus vaccination and the global burden of rotavirus diarrhea among children younger than 5 years. JAMA Pediatrics, 172(10), 958–965.
    url_main: https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamapediatrics/fullarticle/2696431
    date_accessed: '2019-05-19'
    date_published: '2018'
